<p valign="top">SIGNAL(2) avr-Xinu SIGNAL(2)</p>

<p style="margin-top: 1em" valign="top"><b>NAME</b></p>

<p style="margin-left:8%;"><b>signal, signaln</b> &mdash;
signal a semaphore</p>


<p style="margin-top: 1em" valign="top"><b>SYNOPSIS</b></p>

<p style="margin-left:8%;"><i>int</i></p>


<p style="margin-left:14%;"><b>signal</b>(<i>int&nbsp;sem</i>);</p>

<p style="margin-left:8%; margin-top: 1em"><i>int</i></p>


<p style="margin-left:14%;"><b>signaln</b>(<i>int&nbsp;sem</i>,
<i>int&nbsp;count</i>);</p>


<p style="margin-top: 1em" valign="top"><b>DESCRIPTION</b></p>

<p style="margin-left:8%;">In either form, <b>signal</b>
signals semaphore <i>sem</i> and returns SYSERR if the
semaphore does not exist, OK otherwise. The form
<b>signal</b> increments the count of <i>sem</i> by 1 and
frees the next process if any are waiting. The form
<b>signaln</b> increments the semaphore by <i>count</i> and
frees up to <i>count</i> processes if that many are waiting.
Note that <i>signaln(sem, x)</i> is equivalent to executing
<i>signal(sem)</i> x times.</p>

<p style="margin-top: 1em" valign="top"><b>SEE ALSO</b></p>

<p style="margin-left:8%;">scount(2), screate(2),
sdelete(2), sreset(2), wait(2)</p>

